Suppose that \Sigma  is a collection of \mathcal {L}-formulas
    and D is a finite sequence (\phi _{1}, \cdots , \phi _{n}) of \mathcal {L}-formulas.
    We say that D is a deduction from \Sigma  if for each i, 1 \leq  i \leq  n, either

\phi _{i} \in  \Lambda 


\phi _i \in  \Sigma 


There is a rule of inference (\Gamma , \phi _i) such that \Gamma  \subset  \{\phi _1, \cdots , \phi _n\}
If there is a deduction from \Sigma  with \phi  as the last line, we call this a deduction
    from \Sigma  of \phi , and write \Sigma  \vdash  \phi .255mlg-000Pmlg-000P.xmlProposition20241015
Fix sets of \mathcal {L}-formulas \Sigma  and \Lambda  and a collection of rules of inference.
    The set T = \{ \phi  | \Sigma  \vdash  \phi  \} is the smallest set C such that


\Sigma  \subset  C


\Lambda  \subset  C


If (\Gamma , \theta ) is a rule of inference and \Gamma  \subset  C, then \theta  \in  C
We begin by proving the three properties for T.

    We want to show that \Sigma  \subset  T. It is sufficient to show that each \sigma  \in  \Sigma  is in T. Well, for each
    \sigma  \in  \Sigma  we know that \Sigma  \vdash  \sigma  because we can write the one line deduction with just \sigma . Thus,
    \sigma  \in  \Sigma  is in T.
We want to show that \Lambda  \subset  T. It is sufficient to show that each \lambda  \in  \Lambda  is in T. Well, for each
    \lambda  in \Lambda  we know that \Sigma  \vdash  \lambda  because we can write the one line deduction with just \lambda . Thus.
    \lambda  in \Lambda  is in T.
Suppose that (\Gamma , \theta ) is a rule of inference and that \Gamma  \subset  T. We want to show that \theta  \in  T.
    It is sufficient to create a deduction from \Sigma  that ends with \theta . By our supposition that \Gamma  \subset  T,
    we know that each \gamma  \in  T. Thus, \Sigma  \vdash  \gamma  for each \gamma . Consider the deduction that is the concatenation
    of all the deductions ending in a \gamma . From this deduction, we can add the line \theta  because \Gamma  is a subset of the
    preceding lines. Thus, we have constructed a deduction from \Sigma  to \theta .
Now, we want to show that T is the smallest such set that satisfies the aforementioned properties.
    Consider a set C that satisfies the three properties. It is sufficient to show that T \subset  C by
    demonstrating that all \phi  \in  T are also in C. Let \phi  \in  T. There must be deduction from \Sigma  to \phi .
    Suppose that the last line \phi  is justified because it is a logical or non-logical axiom. Then, \phi  is in C by definition.
    Now suppose that \phi  is justified by a rule of inference. Then, there is a (\Gamma , \phi ) such that each \gamma  appears
    deduction. Thus, by straightforward induction we get each \gamma  is in C. Thus, by the third property, \phi  is in C.256mlg-000Gmlg-000G.xmlLogical AxiomsDefinition20241013
