Notes from section 2.2 of the HoTT book310hott-0007hott-0007.xmlTransport & Path LiftingLemma202499Trey Plante
Suppose that P is a type famnily over A and that p : x =_{A} y.
   Then there is a function p_{*} : P(x) \to  P(y).
By induction, we can assume p is refl_{x}. We can take (refl_{x})_{*} : P(x) \to  P(x)
    to be the identity function.
We notate the type family P in which the trasport operation happens with:
transport^{P}(p, -) : P(x) \to  P(y)

A type family P over a type A can be viewed as a property of elements of A that holds for x
if x is inhabited. Thus, transport says that properties are preserved along paths; if P holds for x,
and there is a path from x to y, P holds for y. This is equivalent to saying that
properties (type families) respect equality.
Transportation can also be viewed as a "path liting" operation in a fibration. We consider a type family over A to be a fibration with a base space A and fibers P(x)
    over each x : A. Thus, the total space of the fibration is \Sigma _{(x : A)} P(x). Fibrations have the property that given a path p : x = y in the base space and a point
    u : P(x) we can lift the path p to a path in the total space starting at u.
Let P : A \to  \mathcal {U} be a type family over A and assume we have u : P(x) for some x : A. Then for any p : x = y, we have
    lift(u, p) : (x, u) = (y, p_{*}(u)) in \Sigma _{(x : A)} P(x), such that pr_{1}(lift(u, p)) = p.312hott-0005hott-0005.xmlDependent mapDefinition202494Trey Plante
